column1: Search Efforts Resume at Site of Surfside Building Collapse After Temporary Halt
column2: Search and rescue efforts at the site of the Surfside building collapse resumed on July 1, after operations were temporarily stopped at Champlain Towers South while engineers evaluated the safety of the site, officials said. This footage, released by the Miami-Dade Fire Rescue, shows firefighters searching through rubble, and contains footage of a memorial wall. The Miami Herald reported that recovery efforts were paused for 15 hours and resumed just as President Joe Biden concluded a visit to South Florida. Biden and First Lady Jill Biden met with first responders Thursday. Eighteen people are confirmed to have died, and 145 are still missing, following the collapse. Credit: Miami-Dade Fire Rescue via Storyful

column1: Propane Tank Causes Huge Explosion at House in Michigan
column2: A firefighter approaching a house on fire in Plainfield Township, Michigan, early on July 4 was stopped in his tracks by a massive explosion, dramatic video released by the Plainfield Fire Department shows. The fire, at Pleasant Creek Avenue, was burning in the garage, and spreading to the rest of the house when firefighters arrived, the department said. “A large explosion occurred shortly after arrival, which caused the fire to rapidly spread throughout the home,” they said. The cause of the blast was a propane tank in the garage. All occupants had evacuated at the time of the explosion and no one was injured. Toni Jolman, the homeowner, spoke to Wood TV after the fire, and credited a passing newspaper delivery man with alerting her and her family to the danger. Credit: Patrick DuVall via Storyful

column1: ‘Major’ Storm Damage Delays US Senior Open in Omaha
column2: Storm damage delayed round three of the US Senior Open in Omaha, Nebraska, on Saturday, July 10, officials said. PGA TOUR Champions shared this footage on Saturday morning, showing damaged structures and downed trees on the Omaha Country Club golf course. The PGA TOUR said crews were working to clean up “major” damage after the storm. The National Weather Service issued a severe thunderstorm warning for Omaha and surrounding locations, with forecasters predicting wind speeds up to 75 mph and potential hail. The Omaha Police Department reported downed electrical wires and felled trees as storms swept the city. Credit: PGA TOUR Champions via Storyful
